io.prometheus.client.metrics

Class Counter.Partial

  • java.lang.Object
    • io.prometheus.client.metrics.Metric.Partial
      • io.prometheus.client.metrics.Counter.Partial
  • Enclosing class:
    Counter

    @NotThreadSafe
public class Counter.Partial
extends Metric.Partial

    A derivative of Counter that lets you accumulate labels to build a concrete metric via apply() for mutation with the methods of Counter.Child.

    Warning: All mutations to Counter.Partial are retained. You should not share Counter.Partial between distinct label sets unless you have a parent Counter.Partial that you clone().

    In this example below, we have both a race condition with a nasty outcome that unformedMetric is mutated in both threads and that it is an undefined behavior, which data-type label pair setting wins. 

     Counter.Partial unformedMetric = …;

   new Thread() {
     public void run() {
       unformedMetric.labelPair("system", "cache");
           .labelPair("data-type", "user-profile");  // Difference
           .apply()
           .increment();
     }
   }.start();

   new Thread() {
     public void run() {
       unformedMetric.labelPair("system", "cache");
           .labelPair("data-type", "avatar");  // Difference
           .apply()
           .increment();
     }
   }.start();

    The following is preferable and ThreadSafe: 

     Counter.Partial unformedMetric = …;

   new Thread() {
     public void run() {
       Counter.Partial local = unformedMetric.clone();  // Safe step!

       local.labelPair("system", "cache");
           .labelPair("data-type", "user-profile");  // Difference
           .apply()
           .increment();
     }
   }.start();

   new Thread() {
     public void run() {
       Counter.Partial local = unformedMetric.clone();  // Safe step!

       local.labelPair("system", "cache");
           .labelPair("data-type", "avatar");  // Difference
           .apply()
           .increment();
     }
   }.start();
